        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-11-25T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-11-25T23:00:00-05:00" n="640" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d640">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.6359/11–2648: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-11-26T12:00:00+08:00">November 26, 1948—noon.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 26—1:53 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2327. Re proposed Sino-American survey for Chinese deposits of uranium and allied
                    minerals, we November 23 suggested to Dr. Wong Wen-hao desirability of
                    preventing papers thereon in Chinese hands falling into “unauthorized” hands.
                    Wong indicated he appreciated our position and said he would take appropriate
                    steps.</p>
                <p>November 26 Wu Chao-hung, Vice Chairman of National Resources Commission,
                    informed us he had been instructed by Wong personally to be responsible for
                    papers and that he was taking them in few days to Taiwan.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
